{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594551"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:49:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:49:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15325"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15325"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8016"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8016"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46520"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with fever, headache, and a generalised rash three days after being bitten by her pet rat. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The rat bite on her right index finger appears to have healed well. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 115/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. She has a maculopapular rash on her extremities and multiple painful, swollen joints.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptobacillus moniliformis","Leptospira interrogans","Bartonella henselae","Francisella tularensis","Pasteurella multocida"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of rat bite fever: fever, rash, and polyarthralgia occurring several days after a rat bite. The initial bite wound typically heals before systemic symptoms develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptobacillus moniliformis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of rat bite fever worldwide, including very rase cases in Australia. It is a gram-negative bacillus that is part of the normal oral flora of rats. The infection typically presents 3-10 days after exposure with fever, headache, myalgia, and a characteristic rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeptospira interrogans\u003C/strong\u003E causes leptospirosis, which can be transmitted through contact with rat urine rather than bites. While it can cause fever and myalgia, it typically presents with jaundice and renal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPasteurella multocida\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly associated with cat and dog bites rather than rat bites. It typically causes rapid onset of local cellulitis rather than the systemic symptoms seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrancisella tularensis\u003C/strong\u003E can be transmitted through animal bites but is more commonly associated with rabbit exposure (tularemia). The presentation typically includes ulceration at the bite site and prominent lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/strong\u003E causes cat scratch disease and is not typically associated with rat bites. It presents with regional lymphadenopathy rather than the systemic symptoms seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rat bite fever is most commonly caused by Streptobacillus moniliformis worldwide.","Rat bite fever typically presents with fever, rash, and arthralgia following a rat bite with initial wound healing."],"references":["Dendle C, Looke D. Management of mammalian bites. Aust Fam Physician. 2009;38(11):868-874.","Paul C, O\u0027Brien J, Huffam S, Ridley D. Native valve infective endocarditis: a rare complication of rat bite fever caused by Streptobacillus moniliformis. Med J Aust. 2022;217(11):584-585. doi:10.5694/mja2.51775"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46520"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15325"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46520"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-14T21:36:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-14T21:37:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8016"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHea